### Coordinates of a point on a straight line

- The number axis on the line $x$ is determined by the choice of unit and the choice of an origin at point $O$, which divides the line $x$ into two opposite half-lines - the positive and the negative half-axis.

<img style="margin-inline: auto" src="/blog/axis.png" alt="Axis" title="Axis illustration">

### Cartesian coordinate system
- **in a plane (2D):** consists of two mutually perpendicular number lines, called the $x$-axis and the $y$-axis, that intersect at a point called the origin. Every point in the plane can be uniquely represented by an ordered pair of real numbers $(x,y)$, where $x$ is the coordinate along the $x$-axis and $y$ is the coordinate along the $y$-axis.
- **in a space (3D):** consists of three mutually perpendicular number lines, called the x-axis, y-axis, and z-axis, that intersect at a common point called the origin. Every point in space can be uniquely represented by an ordered triple of real numbers (ùë•,ùë¶,ùëß), where ùë•, ùë¶, and ùëß are the coordinates along the respective axes.

